#90: Pass the torch! What advice would you give to other smokers who are trying to quit? #support
If you can't succesfuly quit cold turkey. Then cut down the cigarettes before bed.By each hour

Thank you for sharing! :)

Ryan gosling ? lol

no more smelling like cigarettes..noo more bad breath no more breathing problems

doing puzzles and crafts im a very hands on Person

Not drinking for the first few weeks helped and driving as little as possible since thats where I smoked most
not thinking about the cigarettes and not going outside when my friends go out for a cigarette

Smoking with my friends and after meal cigarettes

Telling myself it's not worth it ! Problem will still be there after a cigarette
Remind myself why I'm quitting and how much of a money waster it is.

Listen to music and talk to the person in the car if you have someone with you.

Instead of going outside for a cigarette at lunch time I'm gonna be watching a movie or talking to someone.
#77: A common trigger for many smokers is waking up in the morning. Showering right away when you wake up is one way to interrupt this common smoking trigger. How would you do it? #control
I worked out in the morning instead of after work. Healthy start to the day and then also showering in morning. It would definitely help
Shower seems to be the one for me!
Definitely shower!!

#76: To prepare for your Quit Date, think about how you will handle mornings without cigarettes. Post your answers to our questions here and keep them handy for that morning when you might need them! #control
Driving on my way to work with my coffee. I would put perfume on right when I get in car to have myself already smelling good to deter me from smoking
When I first wake up I feel like I need a cigarette to be able to function.Instead I'll have a cup of tea or go for a walk.
Did you know that you can avoid almost all of the negative health consequences of smoking if you quit before you are 30 years old? Does that change how you feel about smoking and quitting? #TDII
Can you really?And it does a little bit but not a whole lot

Well statistically yes, however, these statistics don't necessarily mean that everyone will be fine and these results only relate to long-term consequences. So I would definitely suggest to quit earlier than that or not start in the first place. 10001 isn't your quit day coming up? How are you preparing and how confident are you?
I'm confident that I can do it for the most part. My quit date is February 16th.I'm taking long spaces between cigarettes. So I'm not smoking as much.
Great 10001! Have you received those Nicotine gums and patches and do you plan on using them? Have you already started to prepare your quit day?
I'm going cold turkey I've decided. I have a support system in place and things to do to keep my mind off of cigarettes.
Ok, 10001 - glad to hear that you have decided on what is be best way for you to quit! What will you do to keep your mind off and which alternatives do you have when the craving hits?
I'm gonna be using mints and gum when the cravings hit. And also to keep my mind off of the cigarettes I'll listen to music or talk to someone that doesn't smoke or go for a walk.

That sounds great 10001! Please feel free to reach out to your TSP group for support and remember - it's about taking one step at a time. Every craving you successfully manage and every cigarette you decide not to smoke is a step in the right direction and a great success. Is there anything you would still like to discuss before your quit day?
Not that I can think of at the moment.

Sound good 10001! I will also be online next week if anything comes up. You can take one more look at this checklist before your quit day - but I think you are well prepared :) http://smokefree.gov/steps-to-prepare

I chose number one from my mom. She is always there and a great support system. It has been working for other things as well. 😊

My office is upstairs so I was always take the stairs. I go to gym 4-5 days a week. I have an office job, so I try and get up to walk around frequently to get movement. Once it gets nicer I also want to start hiking on a weekly benefits just to be outside more
Go on a daily walk. Start off with 1 telephone pole length and increase it by 1 everyday

#47: Recent quitters may put on weight for two reasons.1) Without nicotine, your metabolism returns to a normal, slower speed.2) You may eat more to combat the urge to smoke.Is weight gain a big concern for you as you quit? Why or why not?#feelinghealthy
Yes because I already have weight issues which cause health problems for me.
I'm not worried about my weight because id like to gain weight as we speak. So I'd be happy to gain a little.

It was a huge concern of mine. When I quit about 2 years ago I noticed it. But this time I joined the gym at same time and don't eat bad food, only have healthy food in the house and I've actually lost weight now woo ! 💪

I love healthy snacks. Although they're expensiveI like having lollipops.

Mine was actually opposite and I would want a cigarette after I ate. I do carry healthy snacks with me, though. At work I'll bring bananas, strawberries, unsalted cashews and light mozzarella string cheese
I'm with 10017. The after meal cig is one of the best! However, I chew gum or hard candy to get me through the cravings.
Thanks for sharing! Small snacks are great substitutions for a cigarette.

As the photo states, I will make a mental check-list of what needs to be my main focus. Also, I will take the time to 'pat myself on the back', so to speak, for all the hard work I've put in so far. Lastly, take the time to recognize how big of astep I'm about to take, and prepare myself for what 'I Think' my come along this journey.

I actually can't do that because when I think too much about quitting then it makes me want to smoke. #45: In what other ways will your life improve when you don’t smoke? What comes to mind when you think about your smoke-free life? #knowyourself

The list goes on and on
My breathing. I'll be able to breathe to do something!!!

I will be healthier, happier, I'll have more money, I won't smell like cigarettes, and I'll save others around me from having to breathe in my second hand smoke. When I think of my smoke-free life, I think clean, happy, clear, concise thoughts. I think about the things I will be able to do better now then before, because of the shortness of breath I get from having REALLY BAD Childhood Asthma

I asked one of my friends she's not ready right now. But she might be ready in February when my quit date is.
None of my friends smoke (thankfully), they all quit already :)

#43: Make quitting fun. Bet a friend that you can quit on your target date, put your cigarette money aside every day, then if you smoke, forfeit it. Would you try this? Post here and tell us who you bet, what you bet, and how stoked you are to say I TOLD YOU SO. #reinforcement
Uh I might. It'd feel pretty awesome to say I told you so lol. I'd bet my friend megan a bus ticket 'we live in different states'.And I'd be pretty stoke to tell her that lol
I'd def do this bit don't know what I'd bet. I'd love to bet my mom though. She's a smoker and maybe me quitting would give her courage to quit.
I would do this but I know my friends wouldn't pay up lol
Thanks for sharing! :)

When I'm stressed out
Yeah what 10017 said.When I'm stressed as well.
When I'm contemplating picking up another Cancer Stick!

#41: Social situations can be a tricky place for new quitters, especially when alcohol is involved. But you want a social life, right? So practice how you'll decline a smoke before you go out. How would you pass on a cigarette if alcohol is involved? #control
Happy 2015 everyone!
Practice!!! Also don't think about the smoke think about the conversation
Or think more about what your doing. Just keep your mind off the cigarettes as much as possible.
I was in this situation recently, but it was actually an E Cig and my friend passed it to me. I simply said I didn't want any type of nicotine and that was that !

#40: Sometimes, less is more. Today, try smoking only half of each cigarette. Here’s a tip: instead of lighting a whole cigarette and stopping halfway, break half of it off first then finish it. How did it go? Do you think you could do this for all future cigs? #feelinghealthy
I'll give it a try!But no promises I can do it. Normally I'll just have another even sooner. But maybe this time it'll be different

When I was smoking, I don't think I could do that. I would think about what a waste of money it was (even though ALL cigarettes is a waste of money, if I'm trying to quit then every last bit counts until the last one).
Many people associate the beginning of a new year with change. Do you guys have any resolutions for the New Year? #TDII
My New Years resolution is to quit smoking by the time the groups over.
That's great 10001! Have you decided on a quit date yet?
Definitely feb 16th.Will have my last cigarette the night before

Right on, 10001! We'll make sure to prepare you in any way possible for your quit date! At this point I encourage you to tell all your friends and family about your chosen quit date and ask them for their support. Are you ready to do that?
To continue to not smoke and continue to go to gym and eating healthy
Yes! Sure am!
Great 10017! Also, I encourage you to be a resource for others in this group. Your experience and support will help them a lot!

10001 as a small homework to prepare you for your quit day I challenge you to get rid of one specific cigarette you smoke each day. Maybe the first one in the morning, the one after lunch, dinner or after a coffee brake. It is entirely up to you which one. Do you think you can do this?
Yeah I can.I can do the one I normally have right after lunch.Instead I'll wait a hour to a hour and a half.Is that ok?
Yes that's perfect 10001! Do you have any ideas how to deal with the cravings that you may have to face?
I've got to run guys - Happy new year everyone and I look forward to working with you in 2015!

#38: Taking five minutes to sit and breathe can enhance your well-being, mood, attention and mental focus. If you’re feeling stressed today, just take 5 minutes to breathe and tell us if it worked for you. #reinforcement
It didn't really work for me.Just sit here more stressed then I was.
Didn't help me much, honestly.
Thanks for trying it anyways :)
No problem!
That does help me now, but in the past when I've tried quitting I remember it didn't work

#39: The following post was made by a successful quitter: ‘I spent extra time doing things just for me: taking a long bath, reading a good book, or taking a nap. I’m doing a great job at quitting. I deserve to treat myself well!’ How would you treat yourself once YOU quit? #reinforcement
I would treat myself by saving my money that I spend on cigarettes and taking it to go out to dinner with for once.
I'll buy myself little things here and there or go out for a pedicure and remind myself WHY I'm treating myself so I see it as a reward for quitting

Merry Christmas!!!
I did those things and it was great. Also got a car wash inside and out to get ashes and smell out of car
Plan on doing that and Also plan on making sure my mouth is extra clean. And making sure my clean clothes don't smell like smoke and air out the trailer
I plan to do my laundry, so I am smoke-scent free! As well as get a hair cut, so I have fresh hair. Like my start in life, tobacco Free, I want everything Fresh

#33: Here are five really easy substitutions for smoking. Which (if any) of these practical replacements would fit into your life? #feelinghealthy• Chew on a toothpick or coffee stirrer• Tell yourself that you can beat this urge• Hold a pencil, rubber ball, or worry beads• Take a shower - you can’t smoke in there!• Surf the internet
Telling myself I can beat the urge and then holding something like a rubber ball
I'd chew on a top pick and keep telling myself I can beat the urge

#32: Having a mantra that’s motivating and centering that you can repeat to yourself when things get tough can be a HUGE help to deal with cravings. Think of your own mantra or phrase and post it here. #feelinghealthy
When you light it think how your gonna fight it?You'll be broke if you keep on smoking!Something like that?
Love it! :)
Thanks! :)
Hi guys! With the holidays coming up I’d be interested to find out more about your smoking. Any specific smoking triggers coming up for you? #TDII
Just drinking lol but I never smoked around my family anyways so it should be okay
Glad to hear that 10017! Sounds like you are well on track! How have the past couple of weeks been for you? Any difficult situations you had to face? How did you handle them?

I had a stressful time last week with a big presentation I had to put together for my company. People weren't turning their portions into me and I was getting stressed out but I just took deep breaths and it was okay. I seriously just keep telling myself it's not going to help me and if anything if I smoke it'll make it worst because then I'll be disappointed in myself for caving
Great job 10017 - that's exactly what I would recommend! :) Also knowing that cravings usually go away or get considerably less after a couple of minutes can help bridging that critical time period.

I'vegot to run guys. Here are some options that can help you deal with cigarette cravings that may come up. Happy Holidays everyone!http://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-living/quit-smoking/in-depth/nicotine-craving/art-20045454

It'll actually help me breathe and I won't need to catch my breath after quitting.

'I'll believe it when I see it' lol because she's heard me say I'm quitting 20 times. She's proud that I've stuck it out this far though
She wants to do it with me! Although idk if she will but it's nice to hear

#27: Ready to commit to quitting? If yes, pick a date to quit smoking for good! Post it here, or create a group event and invite everyone in this group. Everytime you check Facebook, you’ll be reminded that someone is making the change with you. #freeyourself
It was December 26th.But I'm gonna set feb 14!
^^^^SOOOOO Weird!!! That's My Date!!!! Feb 14th That Is... I Choose This Date Because it's My birthday!! 😊
It's also Valentine's Day! What a coincidence ^_^ So proud to hear that you guys have committed to a Quit Date!
Darn my comment didn't post yesterday: my date WAS November 3rd (last cigarette/nicotine was November 2nd)
Keep up the hard work, 10017 =D

Hi guys - I am online now. Feel free to get in touch if you have any questions. One thing I would like to know from you though: How do you feel about your quitting now? Still feeling committed to staying smoke free? #TDII

I'm feeling like I need to move my date up. But I need your help.If I'm feeling that way should I start using the patches and gum sooner. Or should I wait?I'm going to a house with 2 heavy smokers and another house with another heavy smoker.And I'm not sure if I should wait or start sooner?

HI 10001 - that sounds like a difficult situation and I can see why that can stress you out. In general I would recommend you quit while we are still running this group, since there is an entire support system in place for you. Is there any chance you can ask the smokers you are going to move in with to support you in your efforts? (hint: assertiveness) If you think that's not an option moving the quit date back is of course ok as well. You know yourself and your situation better than I ever will - so in the end it's your decision.
It wouldn't hurt to try sooner right?I'm just going to see them. Not move in. When does this group end again?

To respond to your questions about the nicotine replacement: In general it is recommended you start using them on your quit date. You can take off the patch during the night if that causes you trouble sleeping. That's perfectly fine.

You know chances are there will always be some smokers in your life. So I guess you could postpone your quitting endlessly. Eventually you will have to face other smokers after you have quit. I'm not saying that will be easy, but I think it will probably be somewhat inevitable in the long run. What do you think?

We are posting for 90 days in total (today is #27, I believe), but you will still be a member of the group after that and resources will also still be there. E.g. you can always contact me if you have question/need advice, etc.
I agree with you!!!Is it ok to change quit date sooner. And start like tomorrow. Or should I just go with the original date (the 26th)
I guess you had your reasons for picking the 26th - if that day still seems like a good time you might as well run with it. We can prepare for the day now if you like?
Let me think about it if we have 90 days that's still time to postpone till I come back. I'll only be gone a couple weeks. So let me think about what I wanna do please.

Sure no pressure at all! Whatever you decide is fine with me - I am available anytime. Be that next week or in February. However, I would recommend you still participate in the group and the sessions as everything you will learn here will definitely help you - even if you won't use it immediately.
I definitely and still participating. I like it here. Everyone is nice
Glad to hear that 10001! It's great to have you here and participating!

I've got to run! I will continue to to these Q&A sessions throughout the next weeks, however, I will probably be online at different days/times. I will let you know in advance. The next special smoking cessation advice session will be in the new year. See you!

I'm not sure to be honest. Maybe just the support from my family. Will eventually help.I just don't know if I'm quite ready.

Hmm good question ! Learning better stress coping strategies. I've been doing deep breaths when I get stressed but I need more tips lol I've been craving one really badly yesterday and today but I'm just telling myself the problems will still be there after the cigarette so what's the point
Thanks for sharing. Having family/friend support and stress-reducing strategies are very important contributors to quitting!

Once you’ve quit smoking, situations that were triggers for smoking can now be thought of as high-risk situations for relapse to smoking. What can you do to prepare for these high-risk situations?

Being prepared with a plan for identifying high-risk situations and knowing how you will successfully cope with them can help to prevent slips or relapses. To make your plan:· Identify your high risk situations.· Develop effective strategies to avoid smoking a cigarette in each high risk situation.· Anticipate upcoming high risk situations and be prepared to use the strategies you’ve developed.

Some strategies for these situations include: having a substitute (gum, candy), have mental distractions from thinking about cigarettes (i.e. focusing on what ppl are saying in convos), and leaving the situation (go to gym, etc.)

Sometimes you may have to respond by revealing to others how their behavior/comments make you feel. There are 3 steps to being successful with this: 1. Be neutral when describing their behavior to them2. Use 'I feel' statements to describe how you feel about their comments/behavior3. Let them know what you want from them (i.e. a specific behavior change) that can help you as you quitHow do you think you could use these 3 steps in your situations to respond assertively?

Although other people may not always change their behavior upon your request, using these steps gives you a better chance of getting what you want and will leave you feeling better about yourself and your ability to be assertive.

You've made your plan and prepared for what's ahead. On your Quit Day, remember to take things one day at a time. Slow and steady wins the race! #reinforcement
The night before your Quit Day, make sure you've gotten rid of all your cigarettes, lighters, matches and ashtrays from your car and home.

The night before your Quit Day, put together a non-smoker survival kit, complete with sugarless gum/candy, toothpicks, other substitutes for smoking, a list of your reasons for quitting, and phone numbers/photos of your support people.
The night before your Quit Day, reflect on the fact that tomorrow will be your first day free from cigarette addiction!
After smoking your last cigarette the night before your Quit Day, take a shower, wash your hair, and brush your teeth. Get rid of all the last traces of nicotine!

Hi 10001 - I think it's totally normal that you are nervous as your quit day approaches. Honestly, who wouldn't be? Changes are often accompanied by nervousness or anxiety of sorts and this is not only true for quitting smoking. And yes, chances are it won't be easy, but all of us here at TSP believe in you! Remind yourself about why you are doing it, stick to your quit plan and all the preparations you have made, and take the challenges (every craving) one at a time! You know what they say: A journey of a thousand miles begins with a single step. You can do it!
